{{Infobox United States District Court case | name = United States v. Fricosu | court = [[United States District Court for the District of Colorado]] | image = | imagesize = | caption = | full name = United States of America v. Ramona Camelia Fricosu, a.k.a. Ramona Smith | date decided = | citations = {{cite court |litigants=United States v. Fricosu |vol=841|reporter= F.Supp.2d|page= 1232|pinpoint= |court= United States District Court for the District of Colorado |date= 2012|url=https://scholar.google.com/scholar_case?case=17911977035950841846 |quote=}} | transcripts = | judge = [[Robert E. Blackburn]] | prior actions = | subsequent actions = | holding = | keywords = [[encryption]], [[self-incrimination]] }}
'''''United States v. Fricosu''''', 841 F.Supp.2d 1232 (D. Col 2012), is a [[federal law#United States|federal]] [[criminal law|criminal]] [[legal case|case]] in [[Colorado]] that addressed whether a person can be compelled to reveal his or her [[encryption]] [[passphrase]] or password, despite the [[U.S. Constitution]]'s [[Fifth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fifth Amendment]] protection against [[self-incrimination]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.denverpost.com/news/ci_19669803 |title=Password case reframes Fifth Amendment rights in context of digital world |newspaper=[[Denver Post]] |date=January 4, 2012 |first=John |last=Ingold }}</ref> On January 23, 2012, judge [[Robert E. Blackburn]] held that under the [[All Writs Act]], Fricosu is required to produce an unencrypted hard drive.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.wired.com/images_blogs/threatlevel/2012/01/decrypt.pdf | work=Wired}}</ref>
Fricosu's attorney claimed it was possible she did not remember the password. A month later, Fricosu's ex-husband handed the police a list of potential passwords.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.denverpost.com/breakingnews/ci_20080656 | work=Wired | first=John | last=Ingold | title=Feds unlock suspect's computer without her help}}</ref> One of the passwords worked, rendering the self-incrimination issue moot.
The [[Electronic Frontier Foundation]] filed an [[amicus brief]] in support of Fricosu.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eff.org/node/58527|title=EFF's Amicus Brief in Support of Fricosu|date=2011-07-08|access-date=2016-09-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blogs.computerworld.com/18615/eff_fights_forced_decryption_with_fifth_for_fricosu|title=EFF fights forced file decryption with Fifth, for Fricosu|last=Jennings|first=Richi|access-date=2016-09-25}}</ref>
Fricosu subsequently entered a plea agreement in 2013, meaning that the question of a defendant's right to resist mandatory decryption will not be addressed by a higher court until such time as a future case addressing the same issue arises.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scholar.google.com/scholar_case?case=9185030390462236515&hl=en&as_sdt=6&as_vis=1&oi=scholarr|title=US v. FRICOSU, Dist. Court, D. Colorado 2013 - Google Scholar|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>
